President Donald J. Trump has issued a proclamation declaring January 2019 as National Slavery and Human Trafficking Prevention Month in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the need to actively work towards preventing and ending human trafficking, which is described as a modern form of slavery. It states that human trafficking affects individuals of all ages and demographics and involves various forms of abuse, such as domestic servitude and commercial sexual exploitation. The proclamation highlights the importance of public awareness, education, and collaboration among different sectors in the fight against human trafficking. It also mentions the actions taken by the Trump administration, including the signing of an Executive Order to dismantle transnational criminal organizations involved in human trafficking and efforts to secure the country's Southwest border. The proclamation acknowledges the enforcement efforts of federal departments and agencies and encourages all Americans to participate in ending human trafficking. The proclamation concludes by calling for appropriate programs and activities to observe National Slavery and Human Trafficking Prevention Month.